            "answer_text": "Basically every temperature from about 3 K (the temperature of the cosmic microwave background, the most direct remnant), through 10^12 K (the point at which we start to lose track because the detailed physics hasn't been tested in particle accelerators), probably as far as some limiting temperature around 1.4x10^32 K (the Planck temperature) where quantum effects are expected to modify General Relativity to an extent that further backward extrapolation is pretty much guaranteed to be meaningless.  That is, the Big Bang isn't a single event so much as a scenario where (i) the past is finite and (ii) at every moment of that finite past, the average temperature and density of the universe has been declining. We're still in the Big Bang, just the very slow, boring tail of it. ",
